{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ecdaf20d-8dfe-4d5b-a8f2-1f0bd4f585f4","content":"With MSTest 3.8.2, you can use **constructor injection** for `TestContext` and implement `IAsyncInitialization` for async setup. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    // Synchronous initialization via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Sync setup here (e.g., create objects, set fields)\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous initialization\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Async setup here (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SyncTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task AsyncTest()\n    {\n        await Task.Delay(1);\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext.TestRunDirectory);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- MSTest 3.x injects `TestContext` via the constructor (no need for the property setter pattern).\n- Implement `IAsyncInitialization` (from `Microsoft.Testing.Platform`) for async setup that runs after construction but before each test.\n- This replaces the older `[TestInitialize]` / `async Task` pattern when you want constructor-based DI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"30261983-57bc-4b2f-8ec6-c2891ff0093c","outputTokens":355,"requestId":"EBE3:334824:7AFDCC:82CCEC:6A044E86"},"id":"6cf17622-99d8-42a1-b915-9895d879774c","timestamp":"2026-05-13T10:12:30.547Z","parentId":"c7975893-a248-463b-b1b7-3e858cc2ec4b"}
